Eun-ji will pay for that.

239
00:10:29,295 --> 00:10:30,296
It's zero calories.

240
00:10:31,831 --> 00:10:34,400
Why don't you say hi to her?
Tell her about yourself.

241
00:10:34,467 --> 00:10:35,835
Hello, I'm Chef Son Jong-won.

242
00:10:35,901 --> 00:10:37,570
-What did you say?
-Son Jong…

243
00:10:37,637 --> 00:10:39,171
-Eun-ji!
-Son?

244
00:10:39,238 --> 00:10:41,140
-Your voice changed, Eun-ji.
-Son?

245
00:10:41,207 --> 00:10:43,509
-Son Jong-won? Okay.
-Son Jong-won.

246
00:10:43,576 --> 00:10:44,910
It's nice to meet you.

247
00:10:47,880 --> 00:10:49,715
Why are you starting baby talk?

248
00:10:49,782 --> 00:10:51,517
You can't do that.

249
00:10:51,584 --> 00:10:53,452
It's nice to meet you. Hey.

250
00:10:53,519 --> 00:10:55,788
-Both restaurants got a Michelin star.
-A star.

251
00:10:55,855 --> 00:10:56,922
He has double stars.

252
00:10:56,989 --> 00:10:59,825
-Really? Double stars?
-Chef Double Stars.

253
00:10:59,892 --> 00:11:02,862
What I want to know more is
if he's single.

254
00:11:02,928 --> 00:11:04,163
Should we ask?

255
00:11:04,230 --> 00:11:06,799
-No, I'm not married yet.
-He's not married yet.

256
00:11:06,866 --> 00:11:08,467
I'm not married yet, either.

257
00:11:09,101 --> 00:11:11,237
WHAT ARE THE CHANCES?

258
00:11:12,071 --> 00:11:14,573
We're here today
with Won-young and Eun-ji.

259
00:11:14,640 --> 00:11:17,343
-IVE will release an album soon, right?
-You're right.

260
00:11:17,410 --> 00:11:21,714
This time, we have a pre-release song
called "REBEL HEART."

261
00:11:21,781 --> 00:11:27,787
<i>In February, we'll release an album</i>
<i>titled </i>EMPATHY<i>.</i>

262
00:11:27,853 --> 00:11:29,789
The album is themed around empathy,

263
00:11:29,855 --> 00:11:33,059
so it'll be nice to have the listeners
connect to the songs.

264
00:11:33,125 --> 00:11:34,326
I see.

265
00:11:34,393 --> 00:11:36,095
-It's the song after "HEYA," right?
-Yes.

266
00:11:36,162 --> 00:11:37,963
-You know it so well.
-<i>Heya, heya, heya</i>

267
00:11:38,030 --> 00:11:39,331
<i>I can't resist</i>

268
00:11:42,068 --> 00:11:44,737
-You know it so well. That's right.
-Yes.

269
00:11:44,804 --> 00:11:46,672
What have you been doing lately?

270
00:11:46,739 --> 00:11:48,441
Well, the thing is,

271
00:11:48,507 --> 00:11:50,509
I listen to it too
when my daughter plays it.

272
00:11:50,576 --> 00:11:52,478
-Of course.
-Thank you.

273
00:11:52,545 --> 00:11:56,549
IVE has such a wide variety of fans.

274
00:11:56,615 --> 00:11:57,616
You're right.

275
00:11:57,683 --> 00:12:00,586
And they're even called
the presidents for elementary school kids

276
00:12:00,653 --> 00:12:03,122
because you have that many young fans.

277
00:12:03,189 --> 00:12:05,591
Whenever we hold concerts,

278
00:12:05,658 --> 00:12:09,195
we see many baby DIVEs there.

279
00:12:09,261 --> 00:12:12,832
So on days when we have concerts,
we'll see the words "baby DIVE"

280
00:12:12,898 --> 00:12:15,735
trending on the Internet.

281
00:12:15,801 --> 00:12:18,604
-How cute.
-I believe we have many baby DIVEs.

282
00:12:19,672 --> 00:12:22,842
-The words are so cute too. Baby DIVE.
-Baby DIVE.

283
00:12:22,908 --> 00:12:27,446
Eun-ji, I heard you recently met
a parent to one of the baby DIVEs.

284
00:12:27,513 --> 00:12:29,615
It was on set, actually.

285
00:12:29,682 --> 00:12:31,350
The set for <i>Mr. Trot</i>.

286
00:12:32,251 --> 00:12:34,286
WAIT, ARE YOU TALKING ABOUT ME?

287
00:12:34,353 --> 00:12:38,858
One day, Sung-ju came up to me.

288
00:12:38,924 --> 00:12:42,595
He said, "Is there a way
I can get IVE's CD with autographs?"

289
00:12:42,661 --> 00:12:45,297
-You had to ask her? Oh, gosh.
-To Eun-ji?

290
00:12:45,364 --> 00:12:46,499
I found out later

291
00:12:46,565 --> 00:12:50,770
that his daughter, Min-ju,

292
00:12:50,836 --> 00:12:53,172
-was a serious DIVE.
-Really?

293
00:12:53,239 --> 00:12:54,240
She really is.

294
00:12:54,306 --> 00:12:58,611
I feel quite bad about bothering someone
to ask for something like that.

295
00:12:58,677 --> 00:13:01,514
But here's how difficult it is.

296
00:13:01,580 --> 00:13:03,949
One day, my daughter left home

297
00:13:04,016 --> 00:13:05,718
with her friend at 5 a.m.

298
00:13:05,785 --> 00:13:09,889
She said there was
some limited-edition IVE merch.

299
00:13:09,955 --> 00:13:12,892
So she went out at 5 a.m. to line up.

300
00:13:12,958 --> 00:13:15,728
There were 200 people before her.

301
00:13:15,795 --> 00:13:17,696
So she waited until the 200 were done.

302
00:13:17,763 --> 00:13:18,898
-At 5 a.m.?
-She had to wait.

303
00:13:18,964 --> 00:13:21,133
-Then, she bought the merch.
-She bought it?

304
00:13:21,200 --> 00:13:24,570
By the time she bought it,
it was over 5 p.m.

305
00:13:24,637 --> 00:13:27,506
So I asked,
"Do you like IVE that much?

306
00:13:27,573 --> 00:13:29,008
Wasn't it hard?"

307
00:13:29,074 --> 00:13:30,075
She said she had a great time.

308
00:13:30,142 --> 00:13:33,145
-She had a great time?
-Everyone there was IVE's fan.

309
00:13:33,212 --> 00:13:35,581
-They'd exchange things they made.
-Yes.

310
00:13:35,648 --> 00:13:37,249
Anyway, Mr. Kim. I'm so sorry.

311
00:13:37,316 --> 00:13:40,219
If you feel bad,
then may I have your autograph?

312
00:13:40,953 --> 00:13:44,456
-Really? I'll really do it.
-Make it out to Min-ju, please.

313
00:13:44,523 --> 00:13:45,958
-My gosh.
-That's a dad's heart.

314
00:13:46,025 --> 00:13:49,161
-He's such a good dad.
-It's Min-ju's birthday tomorrow.

315
00:13:49,228 --> 00:13:51,764
-Really?
-Yes, it's her birthday.

316
00:13:51,831 --> 00:13:53,933
-I guess that happens when you're a dad.
-I guess.

317
00:13:53,999 --> 00:13:56,502
I'm sorry to ask, but I also have a son.

318
00:13:57,803 --> 00:14:00,072
I also have a son.

319
00:14:00,139 --> 00:14:02,074
Please tell her I said happy birthday.

320
00:14:02,141 --> 00:14:03,676
-Okay.
-Look how caring he is.

321
00:14:03,742 --> 00:14:05,978
-I got it, Min-ju.
-That's a dad's heart.

322
00:14:06,045 --> 00:14:07,346
Thank you.

323
00:14:07,413 --> 00:14:10,216
Also, Won-young coined
the term "lucky Vicky" last year,

324
00:14:10,282 --> 00:14:13,485
-and it blew up into a huge fad.
-It did.

325
00:14:13,552 --> 00:14:18,290
I somehow found the lucky Vicky spirit
catching onto everyone.

326
00:14:18,357 --> 00:14:21,927
-I didn't expect it to happen.
-So that's why it's Lucky Vicky.

327
00:14:21,994 --> 00:14:23,329
-It was cool.
-It must've been.

328
00:14:23,395 --> 00:14:25,764
Lucky Sung-ju.
Lucky Jung-hwan. Lucky Hyun-suk.

329
00:14:25,831 --> 00:14:26,832
Find an English name.

330
00:14:26,899 --> 00:14:29,735
I think it goes well
when the name ends in "Ki."

331
00:14:29,802 --> 00:14:31,670
-Lucky Roki?
-Lucky Roki?

332
00:14:31,737 --> 00:14:35,241
Chef Kang-rok did the battle twice,

333
00:14:35,307 --> 00:14:36,842
-and he lost both times.
-Yes.

334
00:14:36,909 --> 00:14:39,078
-That's why he feels small.
-Of course.

335
00:14:39,144 --> 00:14:43,048
Won-young, can you show him your support
in the Won-young mindset?

336
00:14:43,115 --> 00:14:46,485
Actually, something immediately
came to my mind.

337
00:14:46,552 --> 00:14:50,522
It's always darkest before the dawn.

338
00:14:50,589 --> 00:14:54,560
So you should wonder
what kind of great luck you'll see soon.

339
00:14:54,627 --> 00:14:58,397
I think it'll be better if you think,
"That means I'm lucky Roki."

340
00:14:59,131 --> 00:15:01,033
<i>Heya, heya, heya</i>

341
00:15:01,100 --> 00:15:02,902
<i>I can't resist</i>

342
00:15:02,968 --> 00:15:05,938
-That's so cool.
-You'll be luckier than others soon.

343
00:15:06,005 --> 00:15:09,275
You can lose three times
and win three times in a row.

344
00:15:09,942 --> 00:15:13,846
-Do this. Try and do this. Now, go…
-What's that?

345
00:15:13,913 --> 00:15:16,682
<i>Heya, heya, heya</i>

346
00:15:16,749 --> 00:15:17,950
Do it. It's good for your health.

347
00:15:18,017 --> 00:15:19,952
-You have to move a little. Do it.
-I love it.

348
00:15:20,019 --> 00:15:22,121
-Pull it up and spin. Ready, go.
-Ready, go.

349
00:15:22,187 --> 00:15:24,290
<i>Heya, heya, heya</i>

350
00:15:24,356 --> 00:15:26,992
-He tried so hard.
-He did.

351
00:15:28,394 --> 00:15:30,362
-I love the seating today.
-<i>I can't resist</i>

352
00:15:30,429 --> 00:15:33,065
<i>I can't resist Kang-rok</i>

353
00:15:33,132 --> 00:15:34,500
LOOKING INTO THE DISTANCE

354
00:15:34,566 --> 00:15:36,068
What do you keep looking at?

355
00:15:37,703 --> 00:15:40,739
What's there? You're scaring me.
Is something there?

356
00:15:40,806 --> 00:15:42,441
Is one of our camera crew there?

357
00:15:42,508 --> 00:15:44,576
-It must be what we can't see.
-It must be.

358
00:15:44,643 --> 00:15:46,645
He keeps looking at something there.

359
00:15:46,712 --> 00:15:48,847
-Is he seeing things? I'm scared.
-Right.

360
00:15:48,914 --> 00:15:52,384
Again, before we open the fridge,

361
00:15:52,451 --> 00:15:55,321
let's find out Won-young's orders

362
00:15:55,387 --> 00:15:58,057
and decide on the contenders.

363
00:15:58,123 --> 00:16:02,161
What kind of dishes does she want to eat?

364
00:16:02,227 --> 00:16:05,097
Let's find out the orders. Show it to us!

365
00:16:05,764 --> 00:16:06,932
The first order.

366
00:16:06,999 --> 00:16:09,134
It's totally rich, creamy Vicky.

367
00:16:09,201 --> 00:16:12,137
First, the most important thing is
that I can't eat anything spicy.

368
00:16:12,204 --> 00:16:15,174
-I see.
-Write that down. No spicy food.

369
00:16:15,240 --> 00:16:16,475
No spicy food.

370
00:16:16,542 --> 00:16:18,077
So you don't eat <i>tteokbokki</i>?

371
00:16:18,143 --> 00:16:20,779
Oddly, I don't really like <i>tteokbokki</i>.

372
00:16:20,846 --> 00:16:22,748
What? I've never seen anyone
who doesn't like it.

373
00:16:22,815 --> 00:16:23,816
-Right?
-Right.

374
00:16:23,882 --> 00:16:26,685
-Everyone loves <i>tteokbokki</i>.
-Everyone.

375
00:16:26,752 --> 00:16:28,454
Won-young doesn't like <i>tteokbokki</i>.

376
00:16:28,520 --> 00:16:31,023
On the other hand, what I love is

377
00:16:31,090 --> 00:16:35,227
dishes that are creamy, rich, and cheesy.

378
00:16:35,294 --> 00:16:37,830
So my first order is rich, creamy Vicky.

379
00:16:37,896 --> 00:16:39,999
-Something rich and creamy.
-Yes.

380
00:16:40,065 --> 00:16:42,301
I think Poong will do a good job on that.

381
00:16:42,368 --> 00:16:43,369
-Me?
-Rich, creamy Vicky?

382
00:16:43,435 --> 00:16:46,038
I can make something
that'll block off her arteries.

383
00:16:46,105 --> 00:16:48,273
-My gosh! No way.
-If she wants that.

384
00:16:48,340 --> 00:16:49,541
If you want it, I can do it.

385
00:16:49,608 --> 00:16:51,477
You can't block off her arteries.

386
00:16:51,543 --> 00:16:53,612
I can make you sweat grease.

387
00:16:53,679 --> 00:16:55,581
-But I can't do that.
-Oh, no.

388
00:16:55,647 --> 00:16:56,882
My arteries?

389
00:16:56,949 --> 00:16:57,983
What's the other order?

390
00:16:59,318 --> 00:17:01,754
Hold your breath, love dining.

391
00:17:01,820 --> 00:17:04,022
<i>Hold your breath, love dive</i>

392
00:17:04,590 --> 00:17:08,427
I'm sorry, but can you do the real thing?
I can't listen to Sung-ju.

393
00:17:08,494 --> 00:17:09,495
-Won-young.
-Just once, please.

394
00:17:09,561 --> 00:17:12,164
<i>Hold your breath, love dive</i>

395
00:17:12,664 --> 00:17:13,665
That's how you do it.

396
00:17:13,732 --> 00:17:15,734
<i>Hold your breath, love dive</i>

397
00:17:15,801 --> 00:17:18,103
-You can't wipe your snot like this.
-I can't?

398
00:17:18,170 --> 00:17:19,338
You're breathing in.

399
00:17:19,405 --> 00:17:20,806
-Breathing in?
-You're breathing in.

400
00:17:20,873 --> 00:17:23,375
My daughter wiped her nose like this.

401
00:17:23,442 --> 00:17:26,311
-Then Min-ju must be right.
-I guess I saw it wrong.

402
00:17:26,378 --> 00:17:27,813
What does this order mean?

403
00:17:27,880 --> 00:17:32,184
I'm the type who loves to admire the food
before I take a bite.

404
00:17:32,918 --> 00:17:35,387
-Naturally, I love dishes
-Fine dining.

405
00:17:35,454 --> 00:17:38,690
that are pretty and delicious,
like at fine dining restaurants.

406
00:17:38,757 --> 00:17:39,758
In 15 minutes?

407
00:17:39,825 --> 00:17:41,093
Yes, that's true.

408
00:17:41,160 --> 00:17:42,394
Can it happen in 15 minutes?

409
00:17:42,461 --> 00:17:46,465
I was wondering if someone can
at least give it a feel. It won't be easy.

410
00:17:47,633 --> 00:17:49,301
We'll see many hold their breaths.

411
00:17:49,368 --> 00:17:53,238
She's telling you to hold your breath
because you won't have time.

412
00:17:53,305 --> 00:17:56,975
First, the rich, creamy Vicky.

413
00:17:57,810 --> 00:17:58,844
HYUN-SUK RAISES HIS HAND

414
00:17:58,911 --> 00:17:59,912
Choi Hyun-suk.

415
00:17:59,978 --> 00:18:02,681
-Yes, Chef Hyun-suk.
-Chef Flounder.

416
00:18:02,748 --> 00:18:05,684
-"Chef Flounder"?
-She said she liked the seaweed soup

417
00:18:05,751 --> 00:18:07,986
-that you made.
-You have so many nicknames.

418
00:18:08,053 --> 00:18:10,656
-Won-young likes it.
-Chef Eighth Place, Chef Flounder.

419
00:18:10,722 --> 00:18:13,092
I'll make the dish you want.

420
00:18:13,158 --> 00:18:14,493
-Okay.
-Is that so?

421
00:18:14,560 --> 00:18:15,561
I'll look forward to it.

422
00:18:15,627 --> 00:18:18,363
The fine dining order is
the only option for returning chefs.

423
00:18:18,430 --> 00:18:22,568
I think that order is
set aside for one person.

424
00:18:22,634 --> 00:18:25,504
SAM KIM CHOOSES(?)
HOLD YOUR BREATH, LOVE DINING

425
00:18:25,571 --> 00:18:26,572
-Chef Sam?
-Chef Sam?

426
00:18:26,638 --> 00:18:27,873
Were you forced into this?

427
00:18:28,440 --> 00:18:30,776
-I'll give it a try. Yes.
-Can you do it?

428
00:18:30,843 --> 00:18:32,778
-Of course, he can.
-It's perfect for him.

429
00:18:32,845 --> 00:18:35,280
Chef Sam takes
"Hold your breath, love dining."

430
00:18:35,347 --> 00:18:37,716
The original chefs are done.

431
00:18:37,783 --> 00:18:39,451
Sung-jun raises his hand!

432
00:18:39,518 --> 00:18:41,120
WHO WILL SUNG-JUN CHOOSE?

433
00:18:41,186 --> 00:18:44,556
Will he fight against Chef Hyun-suk
or Chef Sam?

434
00:18:44,623 --> 00:18:49,194
I'll copy the pose
of the opponent I want to fight against.

435
00:18:49,261 --> 00:18:50,529
HE PICKS CHOI HYUN-SUK

436
00:18:50,596 --> 00:18:51,597
I'll fight him.

437
00:18:51,663 --> 00:18:53,632
I see. We know who it is.

438
00:18:54,233 --> 00:18:55,234
-Yes.
-Gosh.

439
00:18:55,300 --> 00:18:58,237
We'll decide
who'll be the little Choi Hyun-suk

440
00:18:58,303 --> 00:19:00,005
or who'll be the old Matfia.

441
00:19:01,740 --> 00:19:03,809
THEIR PRIDE IS AT STAKE
IN THIS FIGHT FOR NICKNAMES

442
00:19:03,876 --> 00:19:06,345
Will it be little Choi Hyun-suk
or old Kwon Sung-jun?

443
00:19:06,411 --> 00:19:07,579
Old Matfia.

444
00:19:07,646 --> 00:19:09,381
-Old Matfia.
-Old Matfia.

445
00:19:09,448 --> 00:19:10,983
-Old Matfia.
-The way they speak is similar too.

446
00:19:11,049 --> 00:19:12,451
A FIGHT BETWEEN TWO MEN
WITH SIMILAR LINES

447
00:19:12,518 --> 00:19:13,519
He takes his position.

448
00:19:13,585 --> 00:19:16,088
Who'll take the fine dining order?

449
00:19:16,155 --> 00:19:18,357
Wait, someone is receiving pressure now.

450
00:19:18,423 --> 00:19:20,559
Look at that. Yes.

451
00:19:20,626 --> 00:19:21,693
Double Star.

452
00:19:21,760 --> 00:19:25,297
Chef Jong-won is up against Chef Sam.

453
00:19:25,364 --> 00:19:28,934
When I was much younger,

454
00:19:29,001 --> 00:19:32,704
I'd go to a bookstore
and buy his books…

455
00:19:32,771 --> 00:19:33,772
-I see.
-Whoa.

456
00:19:33,839 --> 00:19:35,440
…and eat at his restaurant too.

457
00:19:35,507 --> 00:19:36,508
Thank you.

458
00:19:36,575 --> 00:19:39,411
I grew up watching him.

459
00:19:39,478 --> 00:19:42,114
I'm grateful that
someone so famous said that.

460
00:19:42,181 --> 00:19:43,949
I'll do my best today.

461
00:19:44,850 --> 00:19:45,851
-Okay.
-That's nice.

462
00:19:45,918 --> 00:19:49,955
-It's the good vibes round.
-The round with good vibes.

463
00:19:50,022 --> 00:19:52,257
The good vibes round.

464
00:19:52,324 --> 00:19:56,361
Eun-ji looks quite sad
after Chef Jong-won chose that side.

465
00:19:56,428 --> 00:19:57,829
-It's a bummer.
-So?

466
00:19:57,896 --> 00:19:59,331
Should I stop him from this?

467
00:19:59,398 --> 00:20:01,366
I already know
he's doing that on purpose.

468
00:20:01,433 --> 00:20:03,235
OH, MY

469
00:20:03,302 --> 00:20:05,270
-Is he playing hard to get?
-Yes.

470
00:20:05,337 --> 00:20:07,673
-He's trying to win your attention.
-To get you.

471
00:20:07,739 --> 00:20:08,740
That was so typical.

472
00:20:08,807 --> 00:20:11,710
-He's playing hard to get.
-He's making her jealous.

473
00:20:11,777 --> 00:20:14,446
I already know that
and can play a move after that.

474
00:20:14,513 --> 00:20:16,281
-It's okay.
-It's okay with you?

475
00:20:16,348 --> 00:20:18,550
-My gosh.
-You're cool about it. "Go ahead."

476
00:20:18,617 --> 00:20:19,885
I'll see you later.

477
00:20:19,952 --> 00:20:21,486
FEELING SHY?

478
00:20:21,553 --> 00:20:24,089
Choi Hyun-suk versus Kwon Sung-jun.
Sam Kim versus Song Jong-won.

479
00:20:24,156 --> 00:20:26,525
Man, these battles.

480
00:20:26,592 --> 00:20:29,094
-It's the Western cuisine war.
-It is.

481
00:20:29,161 --> 00:20:32,097
It became such a big match
that it'll be hard

482
00:20:32,164 --> 00:20:34,299
-when I choose…
-It'll be hard.

483
00:20:34,366 --> 00:20:35,834
It'll be really hard.

484
00:20:35,901 --> 00:20:38,203
The choice will be important,

485
00:20:38,270 --> 00:20:40,806
-but first, the ingredients.
-Yes, right.

486
00:20:40,872 --> 00:20:44,176
-I wonder what her ingredients are like.
-That is so.

487
00:20:44,243 --> 00:20:47,879
Is this fridge from your dorm?

488
00:20:47,946 --> 00:20:51,116
Yes, that's why
I pulled out just my ingredients

489
00:20:51,183 --> 00:20:53,619
-and put them in that fridge.
-Good one.

490
00:20:53,685 --> 00:20:55,387
Your members need to eat too.

491
00:20:55,454 --> 00:20:56,455
Yes, that's right.

492
00:20:56,521 --> 00:20:58,357
It's my first time sharing it.

493
00:20:58,423 --> 00:21:00,926
We present Won-young's fridge!

494
00:21:00,993 --> 00:21:04,062
HOW MANY INGREDIENTS DOES SHE HAVE?

495
00:21:04,129 --> 00:21:05,130
Won-young's fridge!

496
00:21:06,198 --> 00:21:07,833
There are a lot.

497
00:21:08,567 --> 00:21:09,935
You have more than I thought.

498
00:21:10,002 --> 00:21:12,738
-Quite a lot, right?
-You have a lot.

499
00:21:12,804 --> 00:21:16,908
These are only hers among the six members,
but she still brought a lot.

500
00:21:16,975 --> 00:21:19,011
-Is that all right?
-That's a relief.

501
00:21:19,077 --> 00:21:20,912
We need to see.

502
00:21:20,979 --> 00:21:23,115
The first shelf. I see some milk.

503
00:21:23,181 --> 00:21:25,284
-Lots of milk, actually.
-Milk.

504
00:21:25,350 --> 00:21:27,619
-You have many different types.
-Yes.

505
00:21:27,686 --> 00:21:31,690
Here's the thing. I really like dessert.

506
00:21:31,757 --> 00:21:33,759
Let's say there's one sweet food.

507
00:21:33,825 --> 00:21:35,360
I bring out three cups

508
00:21:35,427 --> 00:21:38,363
and pour out almond milk,
soy milk, and milk.

509
00:21:38,430 --> 00:21:40,666
Then I drink different milk
with every bite.

510
00:21:41,400 --> 00:21:42,467
You must love milk.

511
00:21:42,534 --> 00:21:44,202
Milk is like a side dish for you.

512
00:21:44,269 --> 00:21:46,571
-He's right.
-You drink all types of milk.

513
00:21:46,638 --> 00:21:48,206
I have a reason, actually.

514
00:21:48,273 --> 00:21:50,208
The dessert tastes different

515
00:21:50,275 --> 00:21:53,712
when I have it
with different types of milk.

516
00:21:55,881 --> 00:21:59,351
I see different types of salt over here.

517
00:22:00,185 --> 00:22:03,155
You must care a lot about salt.

518
00:22:03,221 --> 00:22:05,490
Beef is my favorite food.

519
00:22:05,557 --> 00:22:08,860
And different types of salt
go with different cuts, right?

520
00:22:08,927 --> 00:22:10,495
You're such a gourmet.

521
00:22:10,562 --> 00:22:13,065
-There's salt for tenderloin,
-How did she know?

522
00:22:13,131 --> 00:22:15,734
and there's different salt
for fatty rib eye, right?

523
00:22:15,801 --> 00:22:17,269
Is that so?

524
00:22:17,336 --> 00:22:18,337
She sounds like a gourmet.

525
00:22:18,403 --> 00:22:20,272
She drinks different types of milk

526
00:22:20,339 --> 00:22:22,441
-and different types of salt.
-And salt.

527
00:22:23,041 --> 00:22:24,810
Top blade tastes great with wine.

528
00:22:24,876 --> 00:22:25,877
-Yes.
-Eun-ji.

529
00:22:25,944 --> 00:22:27,412
-May I come over?
-Come over.

530
00:22:28,380 --> 00:22:29,581
I'm going over!

531
00:22:29,648 --> 00:22:31,817
BLINKING

532
00:22:32,718 --> 00:22:35,420
-I see cheese on the second shelf.
-She has lots of ingredients.

533
00:22:35,487 --> 00:22:36,488
-Yes.
-Cheese.

534
00:22:36,555 --> 00:22:38,757
-That's goat cheese.
-Goat cheese?

535
00:22:38,824 --> 00:22:42,060
-It's made with goat milk.
-Goat.

536
00:22:42,127 --> 00:22:43,929
There's a combination I love.

537
00:22:43,995 --> 00:22:48,100
You'll see the orange bottle for honey.

538
00:22:48,166 --> 00:22:50,535
-That's chestnut honey.
-Chestnut honey.

539
00:22:50,602 --> 00:22:53,705
It tastes wonderful with goat cheese.

540
00:22:54,406 --> 00:22:55,407
That sounds good.

541
00:22:55,474 --> 00:22:58,143
It is, and I've never
recommended it to anyone.

542
00:22:58,844 --> 00:23:00,645
-Was this the first time?
-Yes.

543
00:23:00,712 --> 00:23:01,847
The first time on the show.

544
00:23:01,913 --> 00:23:03,648
Goat cheese and chestnut honey.

545
00:23:03,715 --> 00:23:06,418
Don't you think it'll be sold out?

546
00:23:07,018 --> 00:23:09,254
I've never heard of chestnut honey.

547
00:23:09,321 --> 00:23:12,491
-Let's move onto the side. More cheese.
-There's more cheese.

548
00:23:12,557 --> 00:23:14,326
-Gosh, look.
-Tons of cheese.

549
00:23:14,393 --> 00:23:16,027
Why do you have so much wasabi?

550
00:23:16,094 --> 00:23:18,864
They were all made from different regions.

551
00:23:19,731 --> 00:23:20,732
She's a gourmet.

552
00:23:20,799 --> 00:23:22,601
She really is.

553
00:23:22,667 --> 00:23:25,771
I think this is tofu.

554
00:23:25,837 --> 00:23:28,240
-Beans. Do you like beans?
-Yes, I love beans.

555
00:23:29,007 --> 00:23:31,042
I like soy milk,

556
00:23:31,109 --> 00:23:33,245
so I also love beans and soy.

557
00:23:33,311 --> 00:23:35,447
My little one doesn't eat beans.

558
00:23:35,514 --> 00:23:37,482
She picks the beans out
when we mix it with rice.

559
00:23:37,549 --> 00:23:38,550
Most kids do that.

560
00:23:38,617 --> 00:23:43,321
Can you tell baby DIVEs to eat more beans?

561
00:23:43,388 --> 00:23:45,657
-She doesn't?
-My girl won't eat beans.

562
00:23:45,724 --> 00:23:47,092
My baby DIVEs,

563
00:23:47,159 --> 00:23:49,494
don't pick on your food and eat your beans

564
00:23:49,561 --> 00:23:52,230
to grow even taller. Eat up.

565
00:23:52,297 --> 00:23:54,166
Goodness, thank you.

566
00:23:54,232 --> 00:23:55,934
The middle-aged DIVE.

567
00:23:56,701 --> 00:23:58,270
"The middle-aged DIVE"?

568
00:23:58,336 --> 00:24:00,005
I found a great solution.

569
00:24:00,071 --> 00:24:02,007
I can get her to fix all her bad habits.

570
00:24:02,073 --> 00:24:03,442
BABY DIVES' TEACHER

571
00:24:03,508 --> 00:24:04,976
-She'll fix everything.
-Yes.

572
00:24:05,043 --> 00:24:08,013
Let's move on to the vegetable box.

573
00:24:08,079 --> 00:24:10,515
I see veggies in here.

574
00:24:10,582 --> 00:24:11,750
What's this?

575
00:24:11,817 --> 00:24:14,019
-That's arugula.
-Arugula?

576
00:24:14,085 --> 00:24:15,420
-Sprouts?
-Brussels sprouts.

577
00:24:15,487 --> 00:24:16,588
-Brussels sprouts.
-Those are delicious.

578
00:24:16,655 --> 00:24:17,856
-What are these?
-What are these?

579
00:24:17,923 --> 00:24:19,424
-Endive.
-Endive.

580
00:24:19,491 --> 00:24:21,359
It's often used for Western cuisine.

581
00:24:21,426 --> 00:24:23,962
It has a very crunchy texture.

582
00:24:24,029 --> 00:24:25,497
These are lion's manes.

583
00:24:25,564 --> 00:24:27,666
-Lion's mane, right?
-Lion's manes.

584
00:24:27,732 --> 00:24:29,835
-It's not easy to find.
-Mushrooms?

585
00:24:29,901 --> 00:24:34,406
-Lion's manes are my favorite mushroom.
-Lion's manes.

586
00:24:34,473 --> 00:24:36,842
Do you eat this to stay slender?

587
00:24:36,908 --> 00:24:39,244
Or do you eat it because you like it?

588
00:24:39,311 --> 00:24:42,747
Not at all. I really love those.

589
00:24:42,814 --> 00:24:44,316
-Do you love veggies?
-I do.

590
00:24:44,382 --> 00:24:46,351
-It's not to stay slender.
-She loves veggies.

591
00:24:46,418 --> 00:24:48,653
Those are lucky Vicky lion's manes.

592
00:24:50,355 --> 00:24:53,725
And we have peanut butter.

593
00:24:53,792 --> 00:24:54,793
That's right.

594
00:24:54,860 --> 00:24:56,661
-This one.
-What's this?

595
00:24:56,728 --> 00:24:58,630
A pistachio puree of sorts.

596
00:24:58,697 --> 00:24:59,764
-You're right.
-Pistachio.

597
00:24:59,831 --> 00:25:03,468
I'm super into pistachio at the moment.

598
00:25:03,535 --> 00:25:05,036
It's your recent favorite, right?

599
00:25:05,103 --> 00:25:08,039
-I've always loved it.
-Always.

600
00:25:08,106 --> 00:25:09,741
-That's an important point.
-She must love it.

601
00:25:09,808 --> 00:25:13,178
Let's move onto the freezer.

602
00:25:13,245 --> 00:25:15,180
-There are stacks of these.
-Are those meat?

603
00:25:15,247 --> 00:25:16,248
What are those?

604
00:25:16,314 --> 00:25:18,717
-I see.
-Are those pig's feet? No.

605
00:25:19,751 --> 00:25:21,953
-There are lots.
-Are these all different cuts?

606
00:25:22,020 --> 00:25:26,124
Yes, because beef is my favorite food,

607
00:25:26,191 --> 00:25:29,394
I always keep different cuts
of Korean beef in the fridge.

608
00:25:30,295 --> 00:25:33,798
-It's marked with the cut on the back.
-This is sirloin.

609
00:25:33,865 --> 00:25:35,800
Chefs don't have to look back.

610
00:25:35,867 --> 00:25:37,168
We know when we see it.

611
00:25:37,235 --> 00:25:39,170
WOW

612
00:25:39,237 --> 00:25:40,772
My gosh. Fine.

613
00:25:41,840 --> 00:25:43,041
Good for you.

614
00:25:44,609 --> 00:25:45,977
All right, blacksmith.

615
00:25:46,044 --> 00:25:48,146
A BLACKSMITH, NOT A BUTCHER?

616
00:25:48,213 --> 00:25:49,948
"Blacksmith"?

617
00:25:50,015 --> 00:25:52,751
I see some ice cream.

618
00:25:52,817 --> 00:25:54,686
-Ice cream.
-That's a good one.

619
00:25:54,753 --> 00:25:57,923
That's my favorite flavor.

620
00:25:57,989 --> 00:25:59,624
I love that the most too.

621
00:25:59,691 --> 00:26:00,759
What's this? Olive oil?

622
00:26:00,825 --> 00:26:03,929
Olive oil. That's something I like.

623
00:26:03,995 --> 00:26:06,965
And now, we'll use ingredients
from Won-young's fridge

624
00:26:07,032 --> 00:26:08,833
and begin the 15-minute cook-off!

625
00:26:10,635 --> 00:26:13,238
WE'RE GOING TO BEGIN

626
00:26:13,305 --> 00:26:17,342
The first round with ingredients
from Won-young's fridge is

627
00:26:17,409 --> 00:26:20,712
between the original show-off chef,
Chef Hyun-suk

628
00:26:20,779 --> 00:26:23,982
and the new show-off chef, Chef Sung-jun.

629
00:26:24,049 --> 00:26:26,284
It's the Show-off Chef cook-off.

630
00:26:26,351 --> 00:26:27,752
THE SHOW-OFF CHEF COOK-OFF BEGINS

631
00:26:27,819 --> 00:26:29,921
The two are too similar.

632
00:26:29,988 --> 00:26:31,923
-Right?
-They are.

633
00:26:31,990 --> 00:26:35,260
You two probably don't realize it,
but you two make a great duo.

634
00:26:35,327 --> 00:26:36,328
Yes.

635
00:26:37,262 --> 00:26:38,263
They're a great match.

636
00:26:38,330 --> 00:26:41,132
Let me confirm
the current number of stars for them.

637
00:26:41,199 --> 00:26:43,702
The original show-off chef has two stars,

638
00:26:43,768 --> 00:26:46,171
while the new show-off chef has no stars.

639
00:26:46,237 --> 00:26:49,674
Chef Sung-jun, last time you said
you didn't think you could lose.

640
00:26:49,741 --> 00:26:51,276
I don't think I can lose.

641
00:26:51,343 --> 00:26:52,677
The winner is…

642
00:26:52,744 --> 00:26:55,614
THE BITTER LOSS OF HIS FIRST ROUND

643
00:26:55,680 --> 00:26:58,350
I went home and thought long and hard

644
00:26:58,416 --> 00:27:00,151
about why I lost.

645
00:27:00,218 --> 00:27:03,021
I like to analyze things,
so I made my analysis.

646
00:27:03,088 --> 00:27:05,190
There are these lucky shoes I always wear,

647
00:27:05,256 --> 00:27:06,658
and I forgot to put them on.

648
00:27:06,725 --> 00:27:07,826
THESE LUCKY VICKY SHOES

649
00:27:07,892 --> 00:27:10,829
But today, I'm with my lucky shoes,

650
00:27:10,895 --> 00:27:11,896
so I'll probably win.

651
00:27:11,963 --> 00:27:13,632
-Your lucky shoes.
-Lucky shoes.

652
00:27:13,698 --> 00:27:15,300
Why didn't you put them on last time?

653
00:27:15,367 --> 00:27:18,403
Last time, I had to come
with the lucky frying pan,

654
00:27:19,671 --> 00:27:21,006
so I forgot about the shoes.

655
00:27:21,072 --> 00:27:23,541
If you lose today,

656
00:27:23,608 --> 00:27:25,944
the frying pan will be in trouble.

657
00:27:26,011 --> 00:27:27,946
If I lose today, this frying pan will

658
00:27:28,013 --> 00:27:29,114
have to retire.

659
00:27:30,548 --> 00:27:33,685
That means the pan is out of luck.
It's over.

660
00:27:33,752 --> 00:27:35,487
<i>Yes, it's my favorite frying pan.</i>

661
00:27:35,553 --> 00:27:36,788
<i>Favorite frying pan.</i>

662
00:27:36,855 --> 00:27:38,556
<i>I used this to win</i> Culinary Class Wars.

663
00:27:38,623 --> 00:27:40,358
<i>To win</i> Culinary Class Wars?

664
00:27:40,425 --> 00:27:41,893
The winner is Kwon Sung-jun!

665
00:27:45,930 --> 00:27:47,666
I brought them both today.

666
00:27:48,433 --> 00:27:50,502
-He has a big chance.
-Two lucky items.

667
00:27:50,568 --> 00:27:54,005
The fate of the frying pan will
depend on this battle.

668
00:27:54,072 --> 00:27:56,274
What about the shoes?
Will you throw them out too?

669
00:27:56,341 --> 00:27:57,876
The shoes were a bit expensive.

670
00:27:57,942 --> 00:27:59,711
SCRATCHING HEAD

671
00:27:59,778 --> 00:28:01,012
-Put them off.
-I'll use them to work out.

672
00:28:01,079 --> 00:28:04,115
If you'll throw out that pan,
then let me have it.

673
00:28:04,883 --> 00:28:06,484
I'll give it to Poong.

674
00:28:06,551 --> 00:28:07,619
Yes!

675
00:28:07,686 --> 00:28:09,220
I just found out

676
00:28:09,287 --> 00:28:11,523
the two chefs have
a huge gap in years of experience.

677
00:28:11,589 --> 00:28:14,926
Chef Sung-jun was born in 1995,

678
00:28:14,993 --> 00:28:17,896
but Chef Hyun-suk
began his career in 1995.

679
00:28:17,962 --> 00:28:20,031
-Whoa.
-In the year he was born.

680
00:28:20,098 --> 00:28:21,933
You began to cook when he was born.

681
00:28:22,934 --> 00:28:25,937
-We're seeing photos from 1995.
-What?

682
00:28:26,004 --> 00:28:28,139
KWON SUNG-JUN, AGE 1,
CHOI HYUN-SUK, AGE 24

683
00:28:28,206 --> 00:28:30,308
These photos are from 1995.

684
00:28:31,042 --> 00:28:33,611
-Chef Sung-jun, do you remember this?
-How cute.

685
00:28:33,678 --> 00:28:35,480
-I don't.
-You don't remember.

686
00:28:35,547 --> 00:28:37,415
I think I'm about a year old.

687
00:28:37,482 --> 00:28:38,516
-Exactly.
-How cute.

688
00:28:38,583 --> 00:28:39,751
-I get it.
-I was

689
00:28:39,818 --> 00:28:41,086
a year old as a chef.

690
00:28:41,152 --> 00:28:42,721
-Your facial expression is the same.
-Right?

691
00:28:42,787 --> 00:28:44,322
CROSSING ARMS FOR 30 YEARS

692
00:28:44,389 --> 00:28:47,225
-Why are you chuckling?
-Chef Flounder is the same.

693
00:28:47,292 --> 00:28:50,595
He was cooking
while Chef Sung-jun was in baby clothes.

694
00:28:50,662 --> 00:28:52,230
You're right. Gosh.

695
00:28:52,297 --> 00:28:54,232
-That would mean
-Gosh, you are old.

696
00:28:54,299 --> 00:28:57,469
I have worked hard for the last 30 years

697
00:28:57,535 --> 00:28:59,604
to form the elements of my luck.

698
00:29:00,672 --> 00:29:01,673
YAWN

699
00:29:02,574 --> 00:29:03,908
TRYING NOT TO LAUGH

700
00:29:03,975 --> 00:29:05,744
Great job!

701
00:29:05,810 --> 00:29:07,378
You're overusing the lucky Vicky meme.

702
00:29:07,445 --> 00:29:09,948
-Come on.
-Yes, you're overusing it.

703
00:29:10,014 --> 00:29:13,485
Once again, the new chefs
get to choose a perk.

704
00:29:14,052 --> 00:29:16,855
I won't use it today.

705
00:29:16,921 --> 00:29:18,289
-Whoa.
-You won't?

706
00:29:18,356 --> 00:29:19,691
-Really?
-My gosh.

707
00:29:19,758 --> 00:29:21,893
It had a bigger impact
when I lost after using it.

708
00:29:22,961 --> 00:29:24,462
Yes, that's true.

709
00:29:24,529 --> 00:29:26,798
You'll keep thinking about it at home,

710
00:29:28,199 --> 00:29:30,034
CHEF HYUN-SUK'S INGREDIENTS: LION'S MANE,
TRUFFLE DAVID'S PEACH PRESERVES, CAMEMBERT

711
00:29:30,101 --> 00:29:31,970
MOZZARELLA, GOAT CHEESE, CHEDDAR,
STRIP LOIN, CARROT, MILK, BUTTER, AND MORE

712
00:29:32,036 --> 00:29:34,906
CHEF SUNG-JUN'S INGREDIENTS:
PISTACHIO SPREAD, WHITE BALSAMIC VINEGAR,

713
00:29:34,973 --> 00:29:37,976
SOY HOT POT SAUCE, CAMEMBERT, OLIVE OIL,
ARUGULA, STRAWBERRY, MILK

714
00:29:38,042 --> 00:29:40,912
CHESTNUT HONEY, BUTTER, BEEF BRISKET,
GOAT CHEESE, SPAGHETTI

715
00:29:40,979 --> 00:29:44,015
What did you prepare for Won-young?

716
00:29:44,082 --> 00:29:45,150
It's called

717
00:29:45,884 --> 00:29:47,418
Lucky Choi Steak.

718
00:29:47,485 --> 00:29:49,721
-Lucky Choi Steak.
-Lucky Choi Steak.

719
00:29:49,788 --> 00:29:51,756
-Lucky Choi Steak.
-I like it.

720
00:29:51,823 --> 00:29:53,358
-You do? The title?
-Yes.

721
00:29:53,424 --> 00:29:54,726
-Yes.
-I see.

722
00:29:54,793 --> 00:29:58,630
I first began my career
with Italian cuisine.

723
00:29:58,696 --> 00:30:01,800
The Italian dishes I learned
from my teacher would be powerful,

724
00:30:01,866 --> 00:30:04,435
